{
  "doc_id": "59682",
  "text": "There was no significant heterogeneity in the associations with total fat intake, fat types or sources across different histologic subtypes of EOC in this study. In an Italian case-control study, there also were no notable differences in the risk associations with intake of monounsaturated or polyunsaturated fat across histologic subtypes of EOC [CITATION_1] . However, we noted a strong inverse association and a dose-response between intake of long chain n À 3 and risk of endometrioid EOC. A similar inverse association also was observed in analyses of the primary dietary source of n À 3 (dark fish). In contrast, there was no association between intake of long chain n À 3 with risk of serous, clear cell and mucinous EOC. The inverse association between long chain n À 3 intake and risk of endometrioid EOC parallels a recent finding that women with the highest intake of long chain n À 3 were less likely to develop endometriosis [CITATION_2] . Both epidemiological evidence [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] and reports of shared mutations in ARID1A between endometrioid/clear cell EOC and contiguous atypical endometriosis [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] suggest that specific subtypes of endometriomas may be a putative precursor lesion for endometrioid and clear cell EOC. However, we observed no association between intake of long chain n À 3 and risk of clear cell EOC, nor confounding or effect modification by self-reported history of endometriosis, which suggested that n À 3 intake may not be relevant to all endometriosis-related ovarian tumours and/or among all women with endometriosis.",
